{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b5674cfa-93bd-4c70-9678-bd430085e6f7","content":"When `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is set to `1` (via `<startup>` element in app config), it changes how mixed-mode (C++/CLI) assemblies built against CLR v2 are loaded:\n\n**What it does:**\n- Binds CLR v2-targeted mixed-mode assemblies to the **current runtime** (e.g., CLR v4) instead of loading CLR v2 side-by-side.\n- Mimics the .NET 2.0/3.5 activation behavior where only one runtime could be loaded per process.\n\n**Effect on runtime selection:**\n- Without it, loading a v2-built mixed-mode assembly would attempt to activate CLR v2 alongside v4.\n- With it, CLR v4 handles those assemblies directly, avoiding side-by-side CLR loading.\n\n**Typical config:**\n```xml\n<configuration>\n  <startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">\n    <supportedRuntime version=\"v4.0\" />\n  </startup>\n</configuration>\n```\n\n**Key considerations:**\n- Only affects **mixed-mode** (native + managed) assemblies. Pure managed assemblies already unify to CLR v4 automatically.\n- Common when hosting COM components or P/Invoke-heavy libraries built against .NET 2.0/3.5.\n- Not applicable to .NET Core / .NET 5+.\n\nIf you're seeing this in your activation log, it means the hosting process is configured to avoid CLR v2/v4 side-by-side conflicts.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b65eb42-e805-4ece-b78f-68b5a8d02ec5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation logging, specifically about the `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` setting. This is a .NET Framework concept related to how the CLR runtime is selected and activated. Let me answer from my knowledge — this doesn't require code exploration.","outputTokens":455,"requestId":"C3C1:2E977A:1F14EE1:22E6EB6:6A07CA39"},"id":"997e4d39-5dc9-4a35-8731-cc2a8b253018","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:37:08.781Z","parentId":"6a77e60e-89aa-49c9-98e8-ed696e787e91"}
